{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510030","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510030"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:23:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:23:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11476"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11476"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.51,0.28,0.01,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4108"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78792"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4108"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11476"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64141"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2119"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2877"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4861"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4869"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26990"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43233"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44820"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78792"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to her GP with a two month history of fatigue, recurrent fevers and arthralgia. She has a medical history of two miscarriages in the past three years. Her current medications include a pre-pregnancy multivitamin and naproxen. She has no family history of rheumatological disease however her maternal aunt has coeliac disease. On examination her blood pressure is 110/72 mmHg, pulse 84/min and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. Her BMI is 24. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. Some bloods are arranged and show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EANA: 1:360 (\u0026lt;1:80)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERheumatoid factor: 11 (\u0026lt;14)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations would be most useful in confirming the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Full blood count","Anti-Smith","Anti-CCP","Blood culture","Anti-SSA"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is a young woman who presents with a vague history of fatigue, fever and arthralgia. This constellation of symptoms, in addition to her demographics and history of recurrent miscarriage, suggestive of antiphospholipid syndrome, make a provisional diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Esystemic lupus erythmatosus\u003C/strong\u003E (SLE) likely. In addition to this, a family history of coeliac disease suggest a pattern of familial autoimmunity, further supporting this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFurther to this, an ANA of greater than 1:80 and a negative RF suggest the need for further investigation with an \u003Cstrong\u003EENA panel\u003C/strong\u003E, which would aid in confirming the provisional diagnosis of SLE. As such, a positive \u003Cstrong\u003Eanti-smith\u003C/strong\u003E result would be the most useful in confirming a diagnosis of SLE out of the above options. Other diagnostic tests include \u003Cstrong\u003Eanti-dsDNA \u003C/strong\u003E(anti-double stranded DNA) and complement 3 and 4.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E full blood count \u003C/strong\u003Emay demonstrate anaemia, neutropaenia, leucopaenia, lymphopaenia, and thrombocytopenia and is important to order in the evaluation of SLE, however none of these findings are specific for SLE, and therefore it is not diagnostic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-CCP \u003C/strong\u003E(anti-cyclic citrullinated peptide)\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Ecould be considered, and would aid in the diagnosis of Rheumatoid Arthritis, however the patient\u0027s negative RF and elevated ANA suggest a non-rheumatoid-arthritis pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood culture\u003C/strong\u003E may be indicated if that patient has a current fever, however her vitals are all within normal limits and therefore a blood culture would not assist in diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-SSA\u003C/strong\u003E (anti-Sj\u00f6grens syndrome related antigen A) may be elevated in SLE, however is a more appropriate and specific test for Sj\u00f6gren\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A positive anti-Sm on an ENA panel is highly specific for SLE.","Systemic lupus erythematosus often presents with non-specific symptoms such as fatigue, fever, and arthralgia, making specific serological tests crucial for diagnosis."],"references":["Bloch D. Antibodies to double-stranded (ds)DNA, Sm, and U1 RNP. Shmerling R, Curtis M R, editors. UpToDate [Internet]. UpToDate Inc, 2020 [updated 2020 April 20, cited 2021 December 31]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/antibodies-to-double-stranded-ds-dna-sm-and-u1-rnp?search=anti%20smith\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1~41\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1#H158783","Aringer M, Constenbader K, Daikh D, Brinks R, Mosca M, Ramsey-Goldman R et al. 2019 European League Against Rheumatism/American College of Rheumatology Classification Criteria for Systemic Lupus Erythematosus. American College of Rheumatology [Internet]. 2019 [cited 31 December 2021];71(9):1400-1412. Available from: https://www.rheumatology.org/Portals/0/Files/Classification-Criteria-Systemic-Lupus-Erythematosus.pdf","Fernando M, Isenberg D. How to monitor SLE in routine clinical practice. Annals of the Rheumatic Diseases [Internet]. 2005;64(4):524-527. Available from: https://ard.bmj.com/content/64/4/524"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64141"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11476"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64141"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T18:48:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T18:49:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4108"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78792"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type"